nt":"646","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4bqx3","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>The bestselling French novel that Scarlett Johansson went to court over in an attempt to block translation is due out in English next month.</p> <p>The award-winning novelist <a href=\"http://www.lemonde.fr/livres/article/2013/06/07/la-premiere-chose-qu-on-regarde-de-gregoire-delacourt-a-vous-degouter-de-l-amour-et-des-larmes_3426171_3260.html\">Grégoire Delacourt’s La Première Chose Qu’on Regarde </a>(The First Thing You See) opens as mechanic Arthur Dreyfuss is paid a visit by a woman he believes is Johansson. The novel, which has sold 140,000 copies in France, goes on to reveal that the woman is not the American actor, but a lookalike, and the pair embark on a relationship.</p> <p>Johansson <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/may/14/scarlett-johansson-sues-french-author\">sued Delacourt </a>last year, with her lawyer stating that the novel constituted a “violation and fraudulent and illegal exploitation of her name, her reputation and her image”, as well as “defamatory claims about her private life”, and set out to stop it from being translated or adapted into a film. </p> <p>The judge <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/04/scarlett-johansson-wins-french-defamation-case\">agreed that it was defamatory</a>, but threw out her claim that it should not be translated or filmed, and that it “fraudulently exploited her name, her image and her celebrity”. The actor was awarded just €2,500 (£1,600) in damages, and €2,500 in legal costs, rather than the €50,000 she had claimed.</p> <p>“All of Scarlett Johansson’s demands were rejected except one thing that was seen to be an attack in her private life over two relations that she never had,” Emmanuelle Allibert of the publishers J-C Lattès <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/04/scarlett-johansson-wins-french-defamation-case\">told the Guardian at the time</a>. “All her other demands … were rejected, notably that there should be a ban on the book being translated or made into a film. We just have to cut out the bit about the affairs.”</p> <p>Allibert said at the time that the publisher was “open to offers” about an English translation; Weidenfeld &amp; Nicolson has now announced that it will publish The First Thing You See in the UK on 10 September. “What I love about Gregoire’s writing is his ability to see the extraordinary in the ordinary. In both [previous novel] The List of My Desires and The First Thing You See, he takes the everyday aspects of life and makes us see what is so special about things we often take for granted,” said publishing director Kirsty Dunsheath.</p> <p>“Scarlett Johansson looked exhausted. Her hair, somewhere in between two colours, was at war with itself, tumbling loose, flowing, as if in slow motion. Her luscious mouth had lost its usual gloss,” writes Delacourt early in the novel, in Anthea Bell’s English translation. “There were gloomy shadows beneath her eyes where her mascara had smudged, like charcoal. And unfortunately for Arthur Dreyfuss, she was wearing a baggy sweater. A sweater like a sack that did no justice to the actress’s curves, which everyone knew were bewitching, spellbinding.”</p> <p>Bell said that “from very early on it’s clear she is a lookalike”. “You won’t be in any doubt,” she added, praising the novel as “affecting”.</p> <p>Delacourt said the idea for the novel came to him after the publication of a survey in France which said that one out of two girls aged between 15 and 25 were considering cosmetic surgery. “So I asked myself, as an old advertiser, a young writer, and a father of a normal age, what we were doing to our children to stop them liking themselves as they were. And I suspected that appearances (fashion, models, actors) had become a more important model than what is inside,” he said. “So I imagined this encounter between one of the most beautiful girls in the world, and a boy who, like all boys, dreams of the most beautiful girl in the world. And when the surface cracks, we discover what is most important: real beauty is self-esteem.”</p> <p>Delacourt said that two lines had been removed from the book “at my request, because it seemed that they upset Ms Johansson”.</p> <p>He added: “However, all that is in the book concerning this actress is true and well-meant.”</p>","productionOffice":"UK","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"French novel The First Thing You See, about a man’s relationship with a film-star lookalike, will be published in the UK in September","headline":"Novel Scarlett Johannson wanted banned is due out in English","byline":"Alison Flood","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/0ec6ae0c43961da5c432045af3e5b8d5e5bcf60a/652_52_2079_1247/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2015-09-03T00:00:00+01:00","standfirst":"<p>French novel The First Thing You See, about a man’s relationship with a film-star lookalike, will be published in the UK in September</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/aug/27/novel-scarlett-johannson-wanted-banned-english-the-first-thing-you-see-gregoire-delacourt","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2015/aug/27/novel-scarlett-johannson-wanted-banned-english-the-first-thing-you-see-gregoire-delacourt","sectionName":"Books","tags":[{"id":"books/fiction-in-translation","webTitle":"Fiction in translation","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/fiction-in-translation","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/fiction-in-translation","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"film/scarlettjohansson","webTitle":"Scarlett Johansson","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/scarlettjohansson","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/scarlettjohansson","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"books/fiction","webTitle":"Fiction","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/book