icdarUrn":"GD*51443257","width":"140"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/9f252d1eb7a9eeb8f06cf08b5024946a0d56f6e7/41_1169_1940_1166/1940.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"Copyright (c) 2007 Rex Features. No use without permission.","displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/9f252d1eb7a9eeb8f06cf08b5024946a0d56f6e7/41_1169_1940_1166/1940.jpg","source":"ITV/REX","photographer":"ITV/REX","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"he 1981 TV adaptation of Brideshead Revisited.","suppliersReference":"656661bh","height":"1166","credit":"Photograph: ITV/REX/ITV/REX","mediaId":"9f252d1eb7a9eeb8f06cf08b5024946a0d56f6e7","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/9f252d1eb7a9eeb8f06cf08b5024946a0d56f6e7","picdarUrn":"GD*51443257","width":"1940"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/9f252d1eb7a9eeb8f06cf08b5024946a0d56f6e7/41_1169_1940_1166/master/1940.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"Copyright (c) 2007 Rex Features. No use without permission.","displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/9f252d1eb7a9eeb8f06cf08b5024946a0d56f6e7/41_1169_1940_1166/master/1940.jpg","source":"ITV/REX","photographer":"ITV/REX","isMaster":"true","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"he 1981 TV adaptation of Brideshead Revisited.","suppliersReference":"656661bh","height":"1166","credit":"Photograph: ITV/REX/ITV/REX","mediaId":"9f252d1eb7a9eeb8f06cf08b5024946a0d56f6e7","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/9f252d1eb7a9eeb8f06cf08b5024946a0d56f6e7","picdarUrn":"GD*51443257","width":"1940"}}]}],"rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"article","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Top 10 conservative novels","references":[],"webPublicationDate":"2015-08-19T09:48:37Z","fields":{"wordcount":"1244","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4bj3p","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>I wanted to write a book about conservative popular fiction, since I’ve been studying it for decades. Old-fashioned Tory fiction fascinates me, partly because it’s social anthropology, with authors and characters from a different world. The techniques and skills in the splendid writing in these novels are also under-appreciated. </p> <p>John Buchan, <a href=\"http://www.abfar.org.uk/ref/?Author_notes_and_lists:Dornford_Yates\">Dornford Yates</a> and <a href=\"http://www.angelathirkell.org/\">Angela Thirkell</a> are three of the best in this genre, and were phenomenally influential. Buchan was a Conservative Unionist MP for eight years (among many other things). His most famous character, Richard Hannay, is an unreconstructed Rhodesian imperialist, but should be read alongside Buchan’s other heroes in a cast of Conservative politicians and adventurers. Yates staunchly opposed social change in his sparkling social comedies and brilliant thrillers. Thirkell reinvented Trollope’s Barsetshire in 30 novels, making a complex saga of intermarrying county families who laughed at liberals and sneered at socialists.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/audio/2015/aug/14/john-buchan-thirty-nine-steps-podcast\">On the trail of John Buchan's Thirty-Nine Steps – books podcast</a> </p> </aside>  <p>They represent the political and social perspectives that the writers of the left were resisting, from the 1920s to well past the second world war. Yet writers like these are hardly studied or taught. Ignoring fiction of a political colour that you don’t agree with is teaching with blinkers on. Literary history should function as a 360-degree panopticon. </p> <p>It’s also important when reading these novelists to understand how endemic antisemitism and racism was in British literary culture, before the Holocaust and afterwards. No writer of the period was exempt from this, even if it doesn’t always appear in their collected works: read the letters and diaries of TS Eliot and Virginia Woolf to see some startling examples. It’s not good enough just to squeal in outrage at the notorious cases. By reading more widely, we can identify the writers who really relished writing vilely about Jews and Africans, and how often they did it. This doesn’t excuse those who used racist or antisemitic words as a casual echo of their own times, but it will help to put their words in context: as historical usage, not necessarily a malignant choice. </p> <p>I’ve picked my favourite novels from these writers, and from seven other wonderful novelists of the right, but nothing published after the 1960s. I cannot enjoy reading fiction written from Thatcherite conservatism, or set in the greedy and selfish society that her values promoted. </p> <h2><strong>1. <a href=\"http://www.victoriansecrets.co.uk/catalogue/the-good-comrade-by-una-silberrad/\">The Good Comrade</a></strong><strong><a href=\"http://www.victoriansecrets.co.uk/catalogue/the-good-comrade-by-una-silberrad/\"> (1907) by Una L Silberrad</a></strong></h2> <p>Julia Polkington goes to work in Holland as a cook so she can steal a valuable blue tulip bulb and repay her father’s debts. After deciding she can’t do this to her gentle employers, she decides to complete a British spying mission instead, by stealing the formula for a secret explosive, taking a sample home to London hidden in her hat. </p> <p>How can anyone resist this spectacularly inventive spy novel? It’s packed with doughty British patriotism, disdain for the shallow snobberies of the Edwardian middle classes, and is a powerfully realistic love story.</p> <h2><strong>2. <a href=\"http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks03/0301341h.html\">Castle Gay</a></strong><strong><a href=\"http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks03/0301341h.html\"> (1930) by John Buchan</a></strong></h2> <p>A reclusive and pompous newspaper magnate is mistakenly kidnapped and abandoned in a Borders cottage, then returned to civilisation by means of a hillwalking boot-camp and a by-election, to discover he is the target of a political plot.</p> <p>Probably my favourite Buchan novel, this is a romp through the heather, an idyllic walking tour and a masterclass in disguises on the hoof. Buchan’s appreciation for political debate ranges from the hustings to fierce pub arguments, and the default position is always Conservative.</p> <h2><strong>3. <a href=\"http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/19th-september-1931/26/adele-and-co-by-dornford-yates-hodder-and-stough--\">Adèle and Co</a></strong><strong><a href=\"http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/19th-september-1931/26/adele-and-co-by-dornford-yates-hodder-and-stough--\"> (1931) by Dornford Yates</a></strong></h2> <p>The elegant, witty, masterful Pleydell family of White Ladies in Hampshire have their jewels stolen in Paris. Knowing that the French police are simply useless, they set out to detect and recover Daphne’s emerald bracelets and Adèle’s pearls themselves. </p> <p>The best introduction to all of Dornford Yates’s specialities: the thriller, the riotously funny comedy of the upper classes, and the novel of high-speed car chases. Beware of the high-octane snobbery, but it’s brilliantly written.</p> <h2><strong>4. <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/gaudy-night.html\">Gaudy Night</a></strong><strong><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/gaudy-night.html\"> (1935) by Dorothy L Sayers</a></strong></h2> <p>Sayers’ unquestioning acceptance of the social hierarchy, and her passion for Lord Peter Wimsey’s background and social assumptions make her a conservative novelist. Gaudy Night, a great feminist novel, also advocates the conservative status quo. The servants’ loyalty to the college is a metaphor for loyalty to a feudal society, even if the dons wear frocks. And order (it is a detective novel, underneath the romance) must be restored: the most conservative impulse of all.</p> <h2><strong>5. <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/call-of-cthulu-and-other-weird-tales.html\">The Call of Cthulhu and Other Weird Tales</a></strong><strong><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/call-of-cthulu-and-other-weird-tales.html\"> (written up to 1937: this collection published 2011) by HP Lovecraft</a></strong></h2> <p>I am very fond of the weird, especially baroque fantasies from a frothingly reactionary writer like Lovecraft. Frustration and anger breed the best invention, and these visions of a tentacled overlord from under the sea in a different dimension makes so much sense as a metaphor for conservative fears.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"c705daf7a3ddc9440c448ff7740c4026d72a7a48\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/8/19/1439974917542/09187b7e-2fa8-4cfb-b63b-ec7e737497ac-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Nancy Mitford.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Right but not wrong ... Nancy Mitford.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Associated Newspapers/Rex</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <h2><strong>6. <a href=\"http://www.angelathirkell.org/atbrief.htm\">Cheerfulness Breaks In</a></strong><strong><a href=\"http://www.angelathirkell.org/atbrief.htm\"> (1940) by Angela Thirkell</a></strong></h2> <p>War comes to Barsetshire, bringing incomprehensible refugees and revolting evacuees. Southbridge prep school has to find room for an evacuated city school and the incoming headmaster, who is worried about “this new and peculiar world where no one knew what dialectic meant”.</p> <p>Thirkell’s eye for social detail and her unexpected sympathies for otherwise repellent characters make this superb novel of the Home Front a beautifully rounded classic of social history and political commentary.</p> <h2><strong><em>7. </em><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/brideshead-revisited-5.html\">Brideshead Revisited</a></strong><strong><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/brideshead-revisited-5.html\"> (1945) by Evelyn Waugh</a></strong></h2> <p>I’m sorry if this is a predictable choice, but Waugh is the most wonderful Tory writer, and this novel is a glorious elegy for the conservative life he could see disappearing after the second world war. It’s his most readable novel, and such a marvellous evocation of a vanishing prewar life of privilege. Waugh borrowed Thirkell’s obnoxious Captain Hooper from her novel Growing Up (1943) and put him in this novel to represent the ghastly new egalitarian world. </p> <h2><strong>8. <a href=\"https://reading19001950.wordpress.com/2014/10/22/tory-heaven-or-thunder-on-the-right-by-marghanita-laski-1948/\">Tory Heaven</a></strong><strong><a href=\"https://reading19001950.wordpress.com/2014/10/22/tory-heaven-or-thunder-on-the-right-by-marghanita-laski-1948/\"> (1948) by Marghanita Laski</a></strong></h2> <p>“He would sit on a bollard on the meagre allotment of third-class deck in the stern, and stare above him to the Socialist Governor-General … I suppose that chap use to read H G Wells as a lad, he thought resentfully, and think about a Socialist Utopia as a sort of dream that could never come off. And now it’s come off.”</p> <p>Such a clever satire on the miseries of the unhappy Conservatives in postwar Socialist Britain.</p> <h2><strong><em>9. </em><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/blessing-2.html\">The Blessing</a></strong><strong><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/blessing-2.html\"> (1951) by Nancy Mitford</a></strong></h2> <p>“‘Honestly now, which would you prefer as a grandmother – a clever old Jewess who has brought brain and money and Caffieri commodes into the family, or some ass of an actress?’</p> <p>‘I can’t understand you, Grace, you used to seem so very English at home.’”</p> <p>Aristocratic English rose marries aristocratic French count, and two inimical forms of class conservatism and snob values collide, helped to near disaster by their demon son. </p> <h2><strong>10. <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/dr-no.html\">Dr No</a></strong><strong><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/dr-no.html\"> (1958) by Ian Fleming</a></strong></h2> <p>The<strong> </strong>first appearance of James Bond, in all his consumerist playboy majesty. The violence is suggested and dangled, never obtrusive, and the instructions for seduction are detailed and terribly exclusive. But the black man gets killed, the villain isn’t white, and the pretty girl has to join the colonising classes to get on in life.</p> <ul> <li><a href=\"http://www.palgrave.com/page/detail/novelists-against-social-change-kate-macdonald/?isb=9781137457714\">Kate Macdonald’s Novelists Against Social Change</a>, a study of conservative popular fiction from 1920 to 1960, is published by Palgrave Macmillan.</li> </ul>","productionOffice":"UK","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"While their politics may be unappealing, you’re missing out on some expert storytelling and brilliant characterisation if you ignore these books","headline":"Top 10 conservative novels","byline":"Kate Macdonald","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/9f252d1eb7a9eeb8f06cf08b5024946a0d56f6e7/41_1169_1940_1166/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2015-08-26T00:00:00+01:00","standfirst":"<p>While their politics may be unappealing, you’re missing out on some expert storytelling and brilliant characterisation if you ignore these books</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/aug/19/top-10-conservative-novels","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2015/aug/19/top-10-conservative-novels","sectionName":"Books","tags":[{"id":"books/series/toptens","webTitle":"Top 10s","description":"Authors choose their favourite books on their chosen theme","type":"series","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/series/toptens","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/series/toptens","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/fiction","webTitle":"Fiction","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/fiction","apiUrl":"http://content.guard